1
00:00:59,973 --> 00:01:02,203
Heavenly Father, we come before Thee,

2
00:01:02,275 --> 00:01:05,345
knee bent and body bowed

3
00:01:05,345 --> 00:01:07,836
in the humblest way
that we know how.

4
00:01:07,914 --> 00:01:11,611
Father, who controls
and knows all things,

5
00:01:11,718 --> 00:01:16,382
both the living
and dying of all creatures.

6
00:01:16,456 --> 00:01:21,291
Give us the strength and the wisdom
to do Thy work.

7
00:01:21,361 --> 00:01:23,795
ln God's name we pray.

8
00:01:23,864 --> 00:01:27,197
And all God's people say, ''Amen.''

9
00:01:27,267 --> 00:01:28,825
- Amen.

10
00:01:49,156 --> 00:01:51,147
When Agave sobered up,

11
00:01:51,258 --> 00:01:53,021
she looked down and saw
the head of her son Pentheus

12
00:01:53,093 --> 00:01:56,119
- right there in her hands.
- She thought he was a wild animal.

13
00:01:56,196 --> 00:01:57,993
That's how Dionysus got his revenge.

14
00:01:58,064 --> 00:02:00,396
You a heathen, Henry.

15
00:02:00,467 --> 00:02:01,957
You know what l got right here?

16
00:02:02,035 --> 00:02:04,629
- What?
- Some of that very wine.

17
00:02:04,704 --> 00:02:09,971
''When l was a child, l soake as a child.

18
00:02:11,545 --> 00:02:14,514
''l understood as a child.

19
00:02:14,614 --> 00:02:18,050
''l thought as a child.

20
00:02:18,151 --> 00:02:21,211
''But when l became a man,

21
00:02:22,255 --> 00:02:23,813
l put away all childish things.''

22
00:02:47,681 --> 00:02:49,649
Freshman class...

23
00:02:49,716 --> 00:02:54,779
l believe we are the most privileged
people in America,

24
00:02:54,888 --> 00:03:00,827
because we have
the most important job

25
00:03:00,894 --> 00:03:03,158
in America:

26
00:03:03,230 --> 00:03:07,257
the education of our young people.

27
00:03:35,562 --> 00:03:37,154
Trudell!

28
00:03:38,665 --> 00:03:41,099
- Who the hell is he?
- Oh, he's just my husband.

29
00:03:45,205 --> 00:03:47,070
l'm gonna cut your head off.

30
00:03:47,140 --> 00:03:52,442
We must impress upon our young people

31
00:03:52,512 --> 00:03:56,471
that there will be difficulties
that they face.

32
00:03:56,550 --> 00:03:58,609
Come on, Trudell.
Come get this whuppin', boy.

33
00:03:58,718 --> 00:04:00,652
- Get him down, Trudell.
- Scared, ain't ya?

34
00:04:00,754 --> 00:04:02,847
Huh? You with the razor
and twice my size?

35
00:04:02,956 --> 00:04:05,288
They must defeat them!

36
00:04:08,461 --> 00:04:15,264
They must do what they have to do
in order to do what they want to do.

37
00:04:15,335 --> 00:04:17,269
Come on, now.

38
00:04:17,337 --> 00:04:18,895
Come on, baby!

39
00:04:20,473 --> 00:04:24,910
Education is the only way out.

40
00:04:26,246 --> 00:04:29,477
Come on, baby. Get up!
Get up, baby. Come on!

41
00:04:29,583 --> 00:04:32,450
The way out of ignorance--

42
00:04:32,519 --> 00:04:34,180
Like cuttin' people, huh, boy?

43
00:04:34,287 --> 00:04:36,255
Want to cut people, Trudell, huh?

44
00:04:37,624 --> 00:04:39,854
Get your hands off me!

45
00:04:39,926 --> 00:04:41,917
The way out of darkness!

46
00:04:47,667 --> 00:04:51,068
lnto...

47
00:04:51,137 --> 00:04:53,935
the glorious light.

48
00:05:40,120 --> 00:05:41,849
Come on, now! Give it back!

49
00:05:41,921 --> 00:05:44,287
- Give it back!
- ''To our precious Hamilton--''

50
00:05:44,357 --> 00:05:46,621
This isn't funny. Come on.
Dunbar, give it back.

51
00:05:46,693 --> 00:05:49,628
Who do you think you are?
Jesse Owens?

52
00:06:09,816 --> 00:06:12,341
Have a seat.

53
00:06:15,555 --> 00:06:18,524
''l am...

54
00:06:18,625 --> 00:06:21,253
''the darker brother.

55
00:06:21,327 --> 00:06:23,818
''They send me to eat in the kitchen
when company comes.

56
00:06:23,897 --> 00:06:26,297
''But l laugh, and l eat well,

57
00:06:26,366 --> 00:06:29,436
''and l grow strong.

58
00:06:29,436 --> 00:06:32,997
''Tomorrow, l will sit at the table
when company comes.

59
00:06:33,073 --> 00:06:35,064
''Nobody'll dare say to me,

60
00:06:35,141 --> 00:06:37,109
'''Eat in the kitchen' then.

61
00:06:37,177 --> 00:06:42,114
''Besides, they'll see how beautiful l am,

62
00:06:42,182 --> 00:06:44,673
''and be ashamed.

63
00:06:44,751 --> 00:06:49,188
l, too, am America.''

64
00:06:49,255 --> 00:06:51,280
Who wrote that?

65
00:06:53,760 --> 00:06:55,159
Langston Hughes, 1924.

66
00:06:55,228 --> 00:06:57,662
1925.

67
00:06:58,865 --> 00:07:05,327
''Hating you shall be a game
played with cool hands.''

68
00:07:06,606 --> 00:07:11,543
''Memory will lay its hands
upon your breast,

69
00:07:11,611 --> 00:07:15,843
and you will understand my hatred.''

70
00:07:15,949 --> 00:07:18,543
Gwendolyn Bennett wrote that.

71
00:07:18,651 --> 00:07:21,755
She was born in 1902.

72
00:07:21,755 --> 00:07:24,383
Unofficially.

73
00:07:24,457 --> 00:07:26,254
You see, in most states,

74
00:07:26,326 --> 00:07:28,123
Negroes were denied birth certificates,

75
00:07:28,194 --> 00:07:30,788
which means l can
lie about my age the rest of my life.

76
00:07:32,232 --> 00:07:34,496
You think that's funny?

77
00:07:36,069 --> 00:07:38,299
To be born...

78
00:07:38,371 --> 00:07:40,498
without record.

79
00:07:41,641 --> 00:07:44,405
Mr. Reed, hand these out.

80
00:07:44,477 --> 00:07:47,105
l'm going to introduce you
to some new voices this semester.

81
00:07:47,180 --> 00:07:49,546
There's a revolution going on.

82
00:07:49,649 --> 00:07:51,947
ln the North. ln Harlem.

83
00:07:52,051 --> 00:07:54,576
They're changing the way
Negroes in America think.

84
00:07:54,687 --> 00:07:57,884
l'm talking about poets
like Hughes, Bennett,

85
00:07:57,957 --> 00:08:00,323
Zora Neale Hurston, Countee Cullen--

86
00:08:00,460 --> 00:08:02,985
''Some are teethed on a silver spoon,

87
00:08:03,029 --> 00:08:05,827
''with the stars strung up for a rattle.

88
00:08:05,865 --> 00:08:08,231
''l cut my teeth
as a black raccoon--

89
00:08:08,301 --> 00:08:10,735
...for implements of battle.''

90
00:08:17,944 --> 00:08:19,935
Meet me after class.

91
00:08:31,124 --> 00:08:33,752
What's a professor doing
in the middle of the night

92
00:08:33,827 --> 00:08:35,488
dressed like a cotton-chopper?

93
00:08:35,562 --> 00:08:37,621
What is a student doing
in the middle of the night

94
00:08:37,697 --> 00:08:38,857
throwing his life away?

95
00:08:38,932 --> 00:08:40,900
lt's funny. l thought
l was defending myself.

96
00:08:40,967 --> 00:08:43,333
Mm.

97
00:08:43,403 --> 00:08:46,600
l remember you.

98
00:08:46,673 --> 00:08:49,335
Couple of years ago.
Then you disappeared.

99
00:08:49,409 --> 00:08:50,501
What happened?

100
00:08:50,577 --> 00:08:53,375
l come and go whenever it suits me.

101
00:08:53,446 --> 00:08:55,505
- Suspensions?
- Leaves of absence.

102
00:08:57,417 --> 00:08:58,850
Why'd you come back?

103
00:08:58,918 --> 00:09:01,284
School's the only place
you can read all day.

104
00:09:01,354 --> 00:09:03,322
Except prison.

105
00:09:05,825 --> 00:09:07,986
l want you to come by
my house tonight, 7:30.

106
00:09:08,061 --> 00:09:09,995
- Corner of June and Campus.
- Why would l do that?

107
00:09:10,063 --> 00:09:12,293
Holding tryouts for the debate team.

108
00:09:14,801 --> 00:09:17,998
- You sure you want somebody like me?
- No.

109
00:09:18,071 --> 00:09:20,631
That's why you're trying out.

110
00:09:20,707 --> 00:09:22,197
7:30.

111
00:09:22,275 --> 00:09:24,038
June and Campus.

112
00:09:49,035 --> 00:09:53,096
''Driven by the wind and tossed--''

113
00:09:55,375 --> 00:09:57,400
Do well tonight, Junior.

114
00:10:01,814 --> 00:10:04,112
Of the 360 students here at Wiley College,

115
00:10:04,217 --> 00:10:08,313
only 45 of you were brave enough
to try out for the debate team.

116
00:10:08,421 --> 00:10:11,117
Of that 45, only four
of you will remain standing

117
00:10:11,190 --> 00:10:13,283
when the tryouts are over-- why?

118
00:10:13,359 --> 00:10:16,487
Because debate is
blood sport. lt's combat.

119
00:10:16,562 --> 00:10:18,723
But your weapons are words.

120
00:10:18,798 --> 00:10:20,163
Come on in.

121
00:10:20,233 --> 00:10:22,394
Now that Mr. Farmer
has joined us, we can begin.

122
00:10:22,468 --> 00:10:23,765
Sit down, Mr. Farmer.

123
00:10:23,836 --> 00:10:26,202
Not right there. Over there.

124
00:10:26,272 --> 00:10:28,103
- Yes, sir.
- James. Right this way.

125
00:10:28,174 --> 00:10:30,233
Good evening, Mrs. Tolson.

126
00:10:30,310 --> 00:10:32,278
- Evening.
- Excuse me.

127
00:10:32,345 --> 00:10:33,744
We're waiting for you, Mr. Farmer.

128
00:10:33,813 --> 00:10:35,280
l'm going, sir.

129
00:10:35,381 --> 00:10:38,748
Thank you, Mr. Farmer.
You smell very good, Mr. Farmer.

130
00:10:38,818 --> 00:10:41,184
- Thank you, sir.
- You're very welcome.

131
00:10:41,254 --> 00:10:43,051
Gentlemen and lady.

132
00:10:43,122 --> 00:10:45,352
This is...

133
00:10:45,425 --> 00:10:49,418
the hot spot.

134
00:10:49,495 --> 00:10:53,363
You will enter it at your own risk.

135
00:10:53,433 --> 00:10:55,628
Mr. Tolson, what about
the debaters from last year?

136
00:10:55,702 --> 00:10:57,192
Don't ask a question you
already know the answer to.

137
00:10:57,270 --> 00:10:58,532
Get up here. You'll be first.

138
00:10:58,604 --> 00:11:00,196
Get right here. Hot spot.

139
00:11:00,273 --> 00:11:02,298
Debate starts with a proposition.

140
00:11:02,375 --> 00:11:03,899
With an idea-- ''Resolved:

141
00:11:03,977 --> 00:11:07,708
Child labor should be regulated
by the federal government.''

142
00:11:07,780 --> 00:11:09,839
The first debater argues
the affirmative.

143
00:11:09,949 --> 00:11:11,576
Affirmative means
that you are for something.

144
00:11:11,684 --> 00:11:13,208
Mr. Reed will argue the affirmative.

145
00:11:13,319 --> 00:11:14,946
The second debater
argues the negative.

146
00:11:15,054 --> 00:11:16,487
Negative means that you are what?

147
00:11:16,556 --> 00:11:17,488
Against.

148
00:11:17,557 --> 00:11:19,388
Brilliant, Mr. Burgess.

149
00:11:19,459 --> 00:11:22,428
You shall argue
the affirmative, Mr. Reed. Go.

150
00:11:22,495 --> 00:11:26,989
Well, sir, l'd begin with a quote
from the poet Cleghorn.

151
00:11:27,066 --> 00:11:31,264
''The golf links lie so near the mill,

152
00:11:31,337 --> 00:11:34,636
''that almost every day,

153
00:11:34,707 --> 00:11:38,302
''the laboring children
can look out and--

154
00:11:38,378 --> 00:11:40,243
and--''

155
00:11:44,150 --> 00:11:46,618
ls that what you learned
from last year, Mr. Reed?

156
00:11:46,686 --> 00:11:48,950
To start something,
and not finish it?

157
00:11:49,022 --> 00:11:50,580
- ls it?
- No, sir.

158
00:11:50,690 --> 00:11:52,351
Sit down.

159
00:11:55,828 --> 00:11:58,854
Who's next? You? Stand up.

160
00:11:58,931 --> 00:12:01,331
Stand up.

161
00:12:02,769 --> 00:12:05,135
lt's getting late.
How much longer can you hide?

162
00:12:05,204 --> 00:12:07,638
l'm not hiding, sir.
l transferred from my college

163
00:12:07,707 --> 00:12:09,334
just to come here
and try out for your team.

164
00:12:09,409 --> 00:12:10,740
l am deeply moved. What's your name?

165
00:12:10,810 --> 00:12:12,300
Samantha Booke.

166
00:12:12,378 --> 00:12:13,675
- Book?
- With an ''e.''

167
00:12:13,746 --> 00:12:17,204
Arise, Miss Booke. With an ''e.''

168
00:12:18,251 --> 00:12:22,654
lnto the hot spot,
Miss Booke with an ''e.''

169
00:12:22,722 --> 00:12:26,715
You know, there's never been a female
on the debating team, ever.

170
00:12:26,793 --> 00:12:28,420
Yes, sir. l know that.

171
00:12:28,494 --> 00:12:30,860
What makes you think
you should be the first?

172
00:12:30,930 --> 00:12:33,194
Because, sir, l am just as qualified as--

173
00:12:33,266 --> 00:12:34,995
- Quit stammering, Miss Booke.
- ...anybody else here.

174
00:12:35,068 --> 00:12:36,797
- My gender has nothing--
- ''Resolved:

175
00:12:36,869 --> 00:12:39,633
Welfare discourages hard work.''

176
00:12:39,705 --> 00:12:42,833
- You'll argue the negative.
- All right.

177
00:12:42,909 --> 00:12:46,606
Welfare takes away a man's
strongest reason for working,

178
00:12:46,679 --> 00:12:49,273
which is survival.

179
00:12:49,382 --> 00:12:50,940
And that weakens the will of the poor.

180
00:12:51,050 --> 00:12:54,153
How would you rebut that,
Miss Booke with an ''e''?

181
00:12:54,153 --> 00:12:56,246
l would say it does not.

182
00:12:56,355 --> 00:12:59,415
Most of the New Deal
goes to children, anyway,

183
00:12:59,492 --> 00:13:01,653
and to the handicapped,
and to old people--

184
00:13:01,727 --> 00:13:03,160
- ls that fact, or conjecture?
- lt is a fact.

185
00:13:03,229 --> 00:13:05,629
- Speak up.
- lt is a fact.

186
00:13:05,698 --> 00:13:07,461
- What's your source?
- The president.

187
00:13:07,533 --> 00:13:09,899
- Of the United States?
- Yes, sir.

188
00:13:09,969 --> 00:13:13,132
That's your primary source? You spoke
to President Roosevelt personally?

189
00:13:13,206 --> 00:13:15,606
Of course not. l did not
speak to him personally,

190
00:13:15,675 --> 00:13:17,267
but l listened to his Fireside Chat.

191
00:13:17,343 --> 00:13:20,244
- Oh, a radio broadcast.
- Yes.

192
00:13:20,313 --> 00:13:22,474
- Any other sources?
- Well--

193
00:13:22,582 --> 00:13:24,550
Any other sources?

194
00:13:26,886 --> 00:13:28,979
Yes, there are other sources.

195
00:13:29,088 --> 00:13:31,784
Like that look in a mother's eyes
when she can't feed her kids.

196
00:13:31,858 --> 00:13:35,294
Without welfare, Mr. Tolson,
people would be starving.

197
00:13:35,361 --> 00:13:36,521
Who's starving, Miss Booke?

198
00:13:36,596 --> 00:13:38,962
- The unemployed are starving.
- Mr. Burgess here.

199
00:13:39,031 --> 00:13:41,397
He's unemployed.
Obviously, he's not starving.

200
00:13:43,236 --> 00:13:45,500
l drew you in, Miss Booke.

201
00:13:45,571 --> 00:13:49,302
You gave a faulty premise,
so your syllogism fell apart.

202
00:13:49,375 --> 00:13:51,309
- ''Syllogism''?
- Your logic fell apart.

203
00:13:51,377 --> 00:13:53,345
Major premise:
the unemployed are starving.

204
00:13:53,412 --> 00:13:55,903
Minor premise:
Mr. Burgess is unemployed.

205
00:13:56,015 --> 00:13:58,506
Conclusion: Mr. Burgess is starving.

206
00:13:58,618 --> 00:14:01,451
Your major premise was
based on a faulty assumption.

207
00:14:01,521 --> 00:14:04,319
Classic fallacy. Who's next?

208
00:14:11,697 --> 00:14:13,858
You were right.

209
00:14:13,933 --> 00:14:15,161
Tell us your name.

210
00:14:15,234 --> 00:14:17,532
l'm Henry Lowe. With an ''e.''

211
00:14:18,571 --> 00:14:21,540
All right, Mr. Lowe. l will name a subject.

212
00:14:21,607 --> 00:14:24,303
You speak a few words--
a pertinent quote from world literature.

213
00:14:24,377 --> 00:14:25,605
Go ahead.

214
00:14:27,914 --> 00:14:28,938
Beauty.

215
00:14:30,950 --> 00:14:32,440
''l heard the old, old men say,

216
00:14:32,552 --> 00:14:34,918
all that is beautiful
drifts away, like the waters.''

217
00:14:35,988 --> 00:14:37,387
Very good.

218
00:14:37,456 --> 00:14:40,653
History. And name
the author this time.

219
00:14:40,726 --> 00:14:43,820
''History is a nightmare,
from which l am trying to awake.''

220
00:14:43,896 --> 00:14:45,261
James Joyce.

221
00:14:48,367 --> 00:14:50,028
Self-pity.

222
00:14:53,272 --> 00:14:57,504
''l never saw a wild thing
sorry for itself.''

223
00:14:57,577 --> 00:14:58,874
D.H. Lawrence.

224
00:15:00,680 --> 00:15:03,513
l love D.H. Lawrence. Have you ever read--

225
00:15:03,549 --> 00:15:04,607
Mr. Farmer.

226
00:15:04,717 --> 00:15:06,776
Yes, sir?

227
00:15:06,886 --> 00:15:10,322
l have eyes in the back of my head
and ears on both sides. Stand up.

228
00:15:12,758 --> 00:15:17,127
Tell me the irony in the name
''Bethlehem Steel Corporation.''

229
00:15:19,165 --> 00:15:23,465
Bethlehem is the birthplace of Jesus,
Prince of Peace,

230
00:15:23,536 --> 00:15:26,369
and Bethlehem Steel
makes weapons of war.

231
00:15:26,439 --> 00:15:28,907
Very good. Sit down.

232
00:15:30,076 --> 00:15:31,065
Good.

233
00:15:31,143 --> 00:15:32,838
Who's next?

234
00:15:32,979 --> 00:15:34,776
That went well.
How will we know how we did?

235
00:15:34,847 --> 00:15:37,509
- Samantha.

236
00:15:39,085 --> 00:15:41,053
Samantha.

237
00:15:43,422 --> 00:15:45,617
Tolson's tough, isn't he?

238
00:15:45,691 --> 00:15:47,682
He sure is.

239
00:15:48,894 --> 00:15:51,761
l'm James.

240
00:15:51,831 --> 00:15:53,890
ls your father Dr. James Farmer?

241
00:15:53,966 --> 00:15:55,957
Yes... yes, he is.

242
00:15:56,035 --> 00:15:59,436
l'm taking theology from him,
and that man speaks in tongues.

243
00:15:59,505 --> 00:16:01,564
French, Greek, Hebrew, Latin--

244
00:16:01,641 --> 00:16:03,302
How many languages
does he speak?

245
00:16:03,376 --> 00:16:07,472
- Seven languages.
- ''Seven languages.''

246
00:16:07,546 --> 00:16:10,379
He must be the smartest man in Texas.

247
00:16:10,483 --> 00:16:12,383
Well, that's not saying much.

248
00:16:13,519 --> 00:16:16,488
So why do you want
to be on the team?

249
00:16:16,555 --> 00:16:20,150
- l think it would be good training.
- For what?

250
00:16:20,226 --> 00:16:22,558
Bein' a lawyer.

251
00:16:22,628 --> 00:16:25,188
Lawyer? That's great.

252
00:16:25,264 --> 00:16:28,131
You know how many Negro
women practice law in this state?

253
00:16:28,200 --> 00:16:29,462
- Two.
- Exactly.

254
00:16:29,535 --> 00:16:31,560
One of them's my aunt.

255
00:16:31,637 --> 00:16:34,265
Well, look at you, Mr. Farmer.

256
00:16:34,340 --> 00:16:35,898
How old are you, anyway?

